<section id="about" class="py-20 px-6 bg-white dark:bg-slate-900">
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100 mb-8">About</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4 text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
      <p>
        For over a decade, I've been immersed in medical research-starting with
        DICOM imaging and expanding into the messier, more interesting world of
        clinical data: EHR systems like Epic (with certifications across Cogito,
        Clarity, and Caboodle), research databases, and the countless data sources
        that power real clinical studies. Much of my work has focused on neurology
        and cardiology imaging, where precision and scale matter. I also have
        experience with the OMOP Common Data Model, and automating pipelines for ETL.
      </p>
      <p>
        As an application analyst, I've deployed and managed open-source platforms
        to solve concrete research problems, then built the governance and processes
        needed for them to scale enterprise-wide. Our REDCap instance is 21 CFR Part 11
        compliant, and our XNAT integrates directly with the clinical imaging archive,
        which means researchers work with real, production-ready systems. I also help
        manage our HPC cluster, migrating us from OpenPBS to SLURM, and set up GitLab
        to give our teams proper version control and documentation infrastructure.
      </p>
      <p>
        Beyond the technical side, I design business processes and data governance
        policies that actually work, translating between what researchers need and
        what compliance requires. I also collaborate with Rice University on
        cross-institutional imaging studies.
      </p>
    </div>
